Hi stig,

the reason I want to externalize this is to be able to easily modify the JSON object or to create a JSON object "on the fly". In JavaScript, I would write something like this:

```
function postNewBlogPost(author, title, text) {
    http.post(JSON.stringify({"author": author, "title": title, "text": text});
};
```

So if I call 

```
postNewBlogPost('kosta', 'JSON in ObjC', 'I recently discovered...');
```

it would http post the following JSON object to a web service:

```
{
    "author": "kosta",
    "title": "JSON in ObjC",
    "text": "I recently discovered..."
}
```

To do the same in Objective C, I can either do something like:

```
-(void) postNewBlogPostForAuthor:(NSString*)author title:(NSString*)title text:(NSString*)text {
    [http post:[NSString stringWithFormat:@"{"author": "%@", \
        "title": "%@", \
        "text": "%@", \
        }", escape(author), escape(title), escape(text)] ];
}
```

OR write an ObjC JSON literal:

```
-(void) postNewBlogPostForAuthor:(NSString*)author title:(NSString*)title text:(NSString*)text {
    [http post:[jsonWrite stringWithObject:
        [NSDictionary dictionaryWithObjectsAndKeys:
            author, //value
            @"author", //key
            title, //value
            @"title", //key
            text, //value
            @"text", //key
            nil //terminate dictionary
          ] ] ];
}
```

I find the latter much nicer, especially if the JSON objects get big and complex. And the JavaScript in this request is just there to create a skeleton to write such a ObjC JSON literal.

So yes, this would definitly belong to the gh-pages. I completely suck as CSS so I didn't dare to let you pull request my ugly HTML page into your nice gh-pages. Still, I think it's a good idea to add this to the source code too, in case someone needs this, he can just use it locally. But that just details...

About the JavaScript: I'll add some more documentation and then update this pull. It's just very plain JavaScript, nothing too fancy, so it should be readable by anyone. Especially if you already wrote a JSON parser/writer :) Still, if there's anything unclear, please ask!

Cheers,
Kosta

